In Java and many other programming languages, you can't rename a function or variable directly. However, there are ways to achieve this using the `@Deprecated` annotation in combination with method overloading (also known as Method Overriding). 

Here is an example of how it could be done:
```java
public class Try {  
    @Deprecated(since = "1.2", forRemoval = true) // This will mark the old name 'abc' to be removed in a future version (replace with new method). 
                                                    // The annotation `forRemoval` is optional and if present, it means that this deprecated API should not exist anymore at all after specified time.  
    void abc() {}    

    public static void main(String[] args) {        
        Try t = new Try(); 
		t.abc(); // This will call the old method 'abc' and won’t throw any compile-time error as it is deprecated now, but at runtime this line of code can be executed successfully because we are calling a nonDeprecated (public) abc() in our main class which was not marked with @deprecated.
    }  
} 
```    
In the above example `abc` method will become obsolete and won't compile at runtime, but it is still accessible from within your program via calling a non-deprecated (public) abc() in main class which was not marked with @Deprecated. This way you can use old names for new features or methods that are deprecated now due to their removal later on and provide some form of documentation about the change, but still allow access from your current codebase using a non-deprecated method name (`abc()`).

