In Java, we can use inheritance to achieve this. We'll first define a base class `Employee` and then subclass it with different types of employees (e.g., 'Developer', 'Manager'). Here is how you could do that in your codebase using interfaces or abstract classes:

```java
public interface Employee {  // Define an Interface for the common features among all employee type, e.g name and id etc...  
    String getName();     // define methods here as per requirement of each subclass (Developer/Manager) ...     
}                         

// Developers are employees in our company so they have to implement Employee interface 
public class Developer implements Employee {      

    private final String name;  

    public Developer(String name){        // constructor for developer type...         
         this.name = name ;               
    }                                     

    @Override                            
    public String getName()  {             // implement the method from interface Employee ...      
            return "Developer: " +this.name;  
     }                                  
}                                          

// Managers are employees in our company so they have to also implements employee Interface...     
public class Manager implements Employee{       
    private final String name ;  // declare the variable for manager type ...      

    public Manager(String name){             // constructor method of经理类型  
         this.name = name;                    
     }                                        

    @Override                            
    public String getName() {                  // implement methods from interface Employee...     
            return "Manager: " +this.name ; 
        }                                  
}                                                                         
```      
Now you can create a new employee like this `Employee developer = company.createDeveloper("John Doe");` and similarly for manager, use the method as shown above to get their name in string format (i.e., "Manager: John", or" Developer : Jane").  This way we are able to create different types of employees with similar methods but have unique features specifics like 'Developers' having a more detailed information and so on, which is the essence behind polymorphism concept in OOP (Object-Oriented Programming).

